      "severity": "low",
      "mitigation": "Monitor outbox table size. Alert if unpublished event count exceeds threshold (e.g., 1000). Implement TTL-based cleanup of published events (retain for 7 days for debugging, then delete). At 500 events/day, even weeks of retention is trivial."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Implement in three phases. PHASE 1 (Week 1-2): Create the four denormalized read model tables in a 'reporting' schema in the same database. Write a backfill script to populate them from the existing 12 tables. Point the dashboard at these tables. This alone solves the performance problem. PHASE 2 (Week 3-4): Add domain event emission to the write path using the transactional outbox pattern. Build projectors that incrementally update read models from events. Stop running the backfill script. PHASE 3 (If needed): If write volume grows beyond 5K/day or latency requirements tighten, introduce async processing via the outbox poller. For now, synchronous projection in the write transaction is fine at 500 writes/day — it adds <50ms to each write.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "migrations/001_create_reporting_schema.sql — CREATE SCHEMA reporting; four denormalized tables",
      "migrations/002_create_outbox_table.sql — domain_events outbox table with (event_id, aggregate_id, event_type, payload, created_at, published_at)",
      "src/reporting/read_models.sql — DDL for: reporting.orders_by_status(status, count, last_updated), reporting.delivery_success_rates(zone, period, total, successful, rate), reporting.transit_time_by_zone(zone, period, avg_hours, p50_hours, p95_hours, sample_count), reporting.courier_performance(courier_id, courier_name, period, deliveries, success_rate, avg_transit_hours, ranking)",
      "src/reporting/projectors/orders_by_status_projector — listens for OrderStatusChanged, maintains status counts",
      "src/reporting/projectors/delivery_rates_projector — listens for DeliveryCompleted, updates zone-level success rates",
      "src/reporting/projectors/transit_time_projector — listens for DeliveryCompleted, updates zone-level transit time aggregates",
      "src/reporting/projectors/courier_performance_projector — listens for DeliveryCompleted, updates courier-level stats",
      "src/reporting/backfill.sql — one-time script to populate all four read models from the normalized schema",
      "src/reporting/reconciliation.sql — periodic check comparing read model aggregates to write-side source of truth",
      "src/api/dashboard_queries.py — new query endpoints hitting reporting schema only"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Each read model table should be fully denormalized — zero joins at query time. Projectors must be idempotent (processing the same event twice produces the same result). Use upsert (INSERT ON CONFLICT UPDATE) for all projector writes. Version all event schemas from day one. Keep projectors as pure functions: event in, SQL upsert out. No business logic in projectors — they are mechanical transformations.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "DO NOT introduce a message broker (Kafka, RabbitMQ) — at 500 events/day it is pure overhead. Outbox polling or even synchronous projection is the right tool.",
      "DO NOT adopt event sourcing — the existing normalized write model works fine and rewriting it provides no value for this use case.",
      "DO NOT try to make the dashboard real-time consistent — eventual consistency (seconds-level) is the natural and correct model for an operations dashboard.",
      "DO NOT create a single monolithic read model table — each dashboard view gets its own table shaped for its exact query pattern.",
      "DO NOT skip the backfill step — the projectors only handle incremental updates; the 50M existing records need a one-time migration into the read models.",
      "DO NOT forget reconciliation — without periodic verification, read model drift is silent and dangerous."
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 92,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "CQRS is the correct pattern — the read/write asymmetry, query complexity, and performance requirements are textbook indicators",
      "Denormalized read models will solve the performance problem — eliminating 12-table joins on 50M rows is the dominant factor",
      "Event sourcing is NOT needed — the existing write model is stable and functional",
      "A message broker is NOT needed at 500 writes/day — synchronous or outbox-based projection is sufficient",
      "Same-database read models are sufficient for this scale"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Exact read model table schemas — would need to see the actual 12-table schema and dashboard mockups to finalize column selections",
      "Whether Postgres handles the read model well under concurrent dashboard load — depends on number of concurrent dashboard users (not specified)",
      "Backfill duration for 50M records — depends on hardware, indexing, and acceptable maintenance window"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "The operations dashboard tolerates seconds-level staleness (eventual consistency)",
      "The team has operational control over the database (can add schemas, tables, background processes)",
      "Dashboard concurrent user count is moderate (tens, not thousands) — if thousands, a caching layer or separate read database would be needed",
      "The 12-table normalized schema is stable and not undergoing active redesign",
      "500 orders/day includes all write operations (creates + updates + status changes) — if status changes generate 10x more events, the total is still only 5000/day, well within synchronous projection capacity"
    ]
  }
}

